    "created_at": "2016-08-29T23:25:44Z",
    "updated_at": "2016-08-29T23:25:44Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Graphics performance normally isn't a problem with OpenRA, unless the hardware is just way too weak and/or old or the drivers are buggy.\n\nAt least on Win7x64, even a tray i5-2500 'HD' IGP with only 4 EUs is currently enough to play OpenRA fluently (on the rendering side).\nBut to my knowledge, Sandy Bridge IGP's driver support for OGL3.x is incomplete at best.\n\nMy point is, most (i)GPUs that could use a performance uplift probably don't support these newer APIs, a lot of (i)GPUs that _don't need_ a performance uplift don't support these newer APIs, and most GFX hardware that _does_ support these newer APIs doesn't have noteworthy performance issues with OpenRA to begin with (and if any of them do, there's no guarantee a newer API version would help).\n"
  },
